        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> Or the TS query can't get the current file name?\r\n\r\nYes, can be done via a custom directive (although it's not the current file name we're after, but the file name of the current tag. Can be retrieved with `taglist()`). \r\n\r\nI have a small (40sloc) PoC with this working, but it's quite slow for larger help files.\r\n\r\n\r\n<details><summary>Code</summary>\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nlocal parser = assert(vim.treesitter.get_parser(0, 'vimdoc', { error = false }))\r\nvim.treesitter.query.add_directive(\r\n  'set-docs-url!',\r\n  function (match, pattern, buf, pred, metadata)\r\n    local tag = vim.treesitter.get_node_text(match[pred[2]], buf)\r\n    local helpfile = vim.fn.taglist('^' .. tag .. '$')[1]\r\n    if helpfile then\r\n      local htmlpage = vim.fs.basename(helpfile.filename):gsub('%.txt', '.html')\r\n      metadata.url = ('https://neovim.io/doc/user/%s#%s'):format(htmlpage, tag)\r\n    end\r\n  end,\r\n  { force = true }\r\n)\r\n\r\nlocal query = vim.treesitter.query.parse(\r\n  'vimdoc',\r\n  [[\r\n    ((optionlink) @markup.link.url (#set-docs-url! @markup.link.url))\r\n    (taglink\r\n      text: (_) @markup.link.url (#set-docs-url! @markup.link.url))\r\n  ]]\r\n)\r\n\r\nlocal ns = vim.api.nvim_create_namespace('test')\r\nlocal root = parser:parse()[1]:root()\r\nfor _, match, metadata in query:iter_matches(root, 0, 0, -1) do\r\n  for id, nodes in pairs(match) do\r\n    for _, node in ipairs(nodes) do\r\n      local node_data = metadata[id]\r\n      local sl, sc, el, ec = node:range()\r\n      vim.api.nvim_buf_set_extmark(0, ns, sl, sc, {\r\n        end_line = el,\r\n        end_col = ec,\r\n        url = metadata.url\r\n      })\r\n    end\r\n  end\r\nend\r\n```\r\n\r\n</details> \r\n\r\nEDIT1: to prevent the slow opening of help files you can use a WinScrollled autocmd\r\nEDIT2: you can probably also skip the directive and just grab the `@markup.link.url` captures of the current viewport and set their url. Or something like `nvim_set_decoration_provider`?",
